MAKES GREAT MUFFINS! Following the suggestions, I made this recipe with 2 cups sugar and 1/2 cup brown sugar, plus double the cinnamon and nutmeg, and subbed half the oil with applesauce. It makes them just sweet enough. I also reserved half the walnuts to spinkle on top and baked in mutliple sizes: loaf (60 min to bake), regular muffin (12 min), and mini muffin (9 min). The minis were best---filling the batter to the brim of the mini-muffin tin makes gorgeous little 3-bite brunch goodies with the quintessential "muffin top."

Rating: 3
Adding another voice to the chorus: can't imagine this w/3 cups sugar, used 1 cup brown and 1 cup white, which was plenty sweet and let the pumpkin flavor through. Used 1-1/2 tsp ea. cinnamon and nutmeg, but didn't increase the cloves (even a tsp. is a lot of that). Added a generous cup of dried cranberries instead of walnuts; it was good but I think toasted nuts would be better (couldn't use because of allergies). As far as I could tell a 15 oz. can of pumpkin works fine, I didn't add anything to compensate. Two 9x5 loaves baked in more like 60 minutes than 70. Ignore the instruction to serve one the day you make it: this tastes a whole lot better the next day. This is a very pleasant, inexpensive recipe that can be put together in a matter of minutes.

